About the Dataset

This dataset, titled "Dentition of Mammals", originates from the book Clustering Algorithms by John Hartigan (Wiley, 1975). The dataset contains the dentition patterns of various mammals and is specifically designed for exploring biological traits using clustering techniques. It includes 8 key dental traits for each animal, capturing the number of incisors, canines, premolars, and molars in both the top and bottom jaws.

Clustering and Data Preparation: Unlocking Patterns in Tooth Data

Before diving into how I prepared the data for clustering, let’s first break down what clustering is and why it’s so valuable.

What is Clustering?

Clustering is a type of unsupervised learning in machine learning that helps group data points into clusters (or groups) based on their similarities. It doesn’t require labeled data or predefined categories. Instead, it analyzes the patterns in the data and groups together points that are more alike. It’s like sorting puzzle pieces into piles by matching their edges, colors, and patterns.

For example:

  • In biology, clustering can help group species based on physical traits or genetic similarities.
  • In marketing, clustering helps companies group customers by similar behavior, allowing targeted campaigns.
  • In social media, clustering can help detect communities within networks by grouping users who interact more frequently.

For my project, clustering will help me discover groups of mammals with similar tooth patterns, without me telling the algorithm how to classify them. It's a powerful way to unlock hidden patterns in the data.



Types of Teeth

The image below provides a visual representation of the various types of teeth, which are categorized in the dataset. It helps illustrate the different tooth types, including incisors, canines, premolars, and molars, for both the upper and lower jaw.



Data Preparation: Getting the Data Ready for Clustering

Now that you know how valuable clustering is, let’s jump into my project and talk about the process I took to prepare the data. Here’s a simple breakdown of the steps I took:

Step 1: Removing the name field – Each mammal has a unique name, but this doesn’t help when clustering. The goal of clustering is to find similarities, and since every name is different, it would just create unnecessary noise in the data. I removed the names so I could focus on what really matters: the tooth pattern data.

Step 2: Handling correlated features – When I examined the dataset, I noticed that “top canines (C)” and “bottom canines (c)” had very similar values. This makes sense because top and bottom canines typically grow in proportion to one another. Including both could cause redundant information to skew the clustering process, so I chose to remove one (I picked “bottom canines” since the top canines usually have more distinct features in animals). For the same reason, I also removed “bottom molars (m)” and “bottom premolars (p)” as they exhibited similar correlations with their corresponding top teeth.

Highly correlated features like this can confuse the algorithm, making it harder to detect the true patterns in the data. By removing one, I made the analysis cleaner and more reliable.

Step 3: No need for standardization – Often, data needs to be standardized (or scaled) to make sure no single feature dominates the analysis due to differences in magnitude. In this case, all the tooth features had similar scales, so I didn’t need to do any scaling.

#### Calculating silhoutte for range of clusters

library(cluster)

# Calculate average silhouette width for a range of cluster numbers
silhouette_avg <- function(k) {
  km <- kmeans(s1.scaled, centers = k, nstart = 10)
  ss <- silhouette(km$cluster, dist(s1.scaled))
  mean(ss[, 3])
}

sil_values <- sapply(2:20, silhouette_avg)

# Plot Silhouette values
plot(2:20, sil_values, type = "b", pch = 19, frame = FALSE,
     xlab = "Number of Clusters K", ylab = "Average Silhouette Width",
     main = "Silhouette Plot for Optimal K")
